        <para> Before introducing Tamboti's Basic Input forms, we need to talk a little about the structure of bibliographical entries in general. </para>
        <para> Bibliographical entries basically divide into three blocks of information, that is, information
            concerning </para>
        <ul>
            <li>the publication itself, </li>
            <li>the container that the publication occurs in, and</li>
            <li>the location of the publication inside its container.</li>
        </ul>
        <para> Monographs that belong in a monograph series, articles that belong in a periodical and contributions to edited volumes that belong in an anthology all follow
            this pattern. Monographs that occur on their own, monographs that are not part of any series, only have the first block
            of information, but that presents no complications: the last two blocks are simply left empty. 
            The same applies to descriptions of series and periodicals as such.</para>
